I wonder if I should write a medium article on this one.  Sorry for the book--

There will be a race: Innovation v. Compute Powerhouses

A "State Vector" simulator does a lossless quantum execution.   It does this by literally maintaining a model in memory that represents all possible states in the search space in a "state vector" that you can pull out and look at.  For this problem, all you need to do in this mode is find the state, in the state vector that has the highest value.   For this reason, with enough percision, it should find the right answer.

...as you may see though, this would require no less than 2^N bytes of memory (where N=# of qubits).  In practice is likely twice this if they use two bytes per state, so this can only work for small qubit sizes.

I should note that real quantum computers don't expose the state vector.  The way you interface with them is by taking a lot of "shots" -- each shot will be one of the possible values from the search space-- so you take millions of these, and all algorithms use the output distribution, to inform the answer to the original problem.

The Default Miner uses Qiskit's AER simulator, which will pick a simulator from it's portfolio, unless you explicitly tell it what to use.  If your system memory supports it, it seems to use StateVector, but then it will switch to other simulators that do lossy simulation that make trade offs to try to solve the problem, in an approximate way, with the resources you have.  
--With these, like a Quantum Computer, you pretty much need to take shots, which takes WAY longer than just inspecting the state vector (which was pretty much a short cut anyway).  
--If your simulator took an approach that was overly lossy, then you might get the wrong answer.  

So what do you do?  

Option 1: More Memory -- this will only work to a point
Option 2: Experiment -- instead of letting AER pick your simulator, you specify it and it's config-- what works?
Option 3: Understand the problem-- can you pre-process?  Can you do something trickier and problem specific?
